{[showcards W:S9 N:S6]

The bidding has been as shown. Partner led the \S9, dummy played the \S6 

Play the \S8 (to signal encouragement).

You could easily win the \SK, then play a small \S to drive out dummy's \SA. But North bid Notrump over your 2\S overcall, so he surely holds \S Q J 10. So when you get the lead with your one \CA entry you can establish your \Ss, but you won't get into the lead to cash them.

Look what happens when you duck the first trick. North will win the trick with his \ST, and start on dummy's \C suit.

East (your wonderful partner) will win the first \C and return his final \S to dummy's \SA.

North will have to keep working on \Cs, but now you can win the \CA and play your \SK, dropping North's \SQ, and your other three good \Ss.

Just like the previous deal, North gets two \S tricks either way, but one way he makes an overtrick, the other way he goes down 2.}
[Play "W"]S9

